{{short description|Third era of the Archean Eon}}
{{Geological eon}}
{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}
{{Life timeline}}
The '''Mesoarchean''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|m|iː|z|oʊ|ɑr|ˈ|k|iː|ə|n}}, also spelled '''Mesoarchaean''') is a [[geology|geologic]] [[era (geology)|era]] within the [[Archean Eon]], spanning {{Ma|Mesoarchean|Neoarchean}}. The era is defined [[Absolute dating|chronometrically]] and is not referenced to a specific level in a rock section on Earth. [[Fossil]]s from [[Australia]] show that [[stromatolite]]s have lived on Earth since the Mesoarchean. The Pongola [[Glacial period|glaciation]] occurred around {{Ma|2900}}.<ref name="Kopp">{{cite journal |author1=Robert E. Kopp |author2=Joseph L. Kirschvink |author3=Isaac A. Hilburn |author4=Cody Z. Nash  |last-author-amp=yes | title=The Paleoproterozoic snowball Earth: A climate disaster triggered by the evolution of oxygenic photosynthesis | journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | year=2005 | volume=102 | issue=32 | pages=11131–6 | url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/0504878102v1 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0504878102 | pmid=16061801 | pmc=1183582|bibcode = 2005PNAS..10211131K }}</ref> The first [[supercontinent]] [[Vaalbara]] broke up during this era about {{Ma|2800}}.

The earliest reefs date from this era, and were probably formed by stromatolites.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Allwood|first1=Abigail C.|last2=Walter|first2=Malcolm R.|last3=Kamber|first3=Balz S.|last4=Marshall|first4=Craig P.|last5=Burch|first5=Ian W.|title=Stromatolite reef from the Early Archaean era of Australia|journal=Nature|date=8 June 2006|volume=441|issue=7094|pages=714–718|doi=10.1038/nature04764|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature04764|accessdate=10 March 2018|bibcode=2006Natur.441..714A}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Jon|title=Stromatolites: Our Mysterious Ancient Reefs|url=https://www.lakesuperior.com/the-lake/natural-world/192feature/|website=Lake Superior Magazine|accessdate=10 March 2018|date=15 April 1997}}</ref> The surface temperature during the Mesoarchean was likely not much higher than modern-day temperatures.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sleep|first1=Norman H.|last2=Hessler|first2=Angela M.|title=Weathering of quartz as an Archean climatic indicator|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|date=January 2006|volume=241|issue=3-4|pages=594–602|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2005.11.020|url=https://geosci.uchicago.edu/~archer/deep_earth_readings/sleep.2006.archean_weat.pdf|accessdate=10 March 2018|bibcode=2006E&PSL.241..594S}}</ref> Atmospheric carbon dioxide concentration was only a few times higher than its pre-industrial value<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marty|first1=Bernard|last2=Zimmermann|first2=Laurent|last3=Pujol|first3=Magali|last4=Burgess|first4=Ray|last5=Philippot|first5=Pascal|title=Nitrogen Isotopic Composition and Density of the Archean Atmosphere|journal=Science|date=4 October 2013|volume=342|issue=6154|pages=101–104|doi=10.1126/science.1240971|url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/342/6154/101.short|accessdate=10 March 2018|language=en|issn=0036-8075|arxiv=1405.6337|bibcode=2013Sci...342..101M}}</ref>, and the Sun's luminosity was only 70% of its current value, cancelling out the influence of a greater degree of greenhouse effect that may be operating.

